'''Tenso Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine''' (天祖若宮八幡宮) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}} located in Sekimachikita 3-chome, {{ill|Nerima Ward|ja|練馬区}}, {{ill|Tokyo Metropolis|ja|東京都}}, Japan. The shrine is situated atop a hill in {{ill|Musashiseki Park|ja|武蔵関公園}}, maintained by Nerima Ward.

== Overview ==

In [[1974]] ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和}} 49), Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine and Tenso Shrine were merged and began to be collectively referred to as Tenso Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine.{{sfn|Nerima Ward Board of Education}}{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}} The enshrined deities include {{ill|Ōhirume-no-Muchi-no-Mikoto|ja|大日孁貴女尊}}, {{ill|Sayori Hime no Mikoto|ja|狭依姫命}}, and {{ill|Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|ja|倉稲魂命}} at Tenso Shrine. Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine venerates {{ill|Hachiman Ōkami|ja|八幡大神}}, identified with {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇}}, and {{ill|Emperor Nintoku|ja|仁徳天皇}}. The main festival is held annually on September 28.{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}}

== History ==

[[File:天祖若宮八幡宮－２.jpg|thumb|Tenso Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine]]
[[File:天祖若宮八幡宮－３.jpg|thumb|Shrine grounds]]

Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine is said to have been established during the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代}} as the guardian deity of the Musashi Seki Barrier.{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}} After the barrier was dismantled, it served as the {{ill|ujigami|ja|氏神}} (guardian deity) of Sekimura, which encompasses present-day Sekimachikita, Sekimachi Minami, Sekimachi Higashi, and Tatemachi. The shrine's role was formalized during the {{ill|Keichō era|ja|慶長}} with the opening of Sekimura.

Tenso Shrine was originally referred to as "Banjin-sama" (番神さま), as described in the "Sekimura" section of the {{ill|Shinpen Musashi Fudokikō|ja|新編武蔵風土記稿}}: "The Banshin Shrine is the village's guardian deity and belongs to {{ill|Hondatsugi Temple|ja|本立寺}}."<ref>{{cite book|和書|title=新編武蔵風土記稿|volume=Volume 13, Toshima District Part 5|chapter=Sekimura|id={{NDLJP|763977/46}}|publisher=Geographical Bureau, Ministry of Home Affairs|date=1884-6}}</ref> During the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新}}, it was renamed Tenso Shrine due to the policy of {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離}}.

== Transportation ==

The shrine is surrounded by dense greenery and forms part of the verdant landscape of Musashino, along with {{ill|Musashiseki Park|ja|武蔵関公園}}, which features a boating pond.

* 5 minutes' walk from {{ill|Musashiseki Station|ja|武蔵関駅}} on the {{ill|Seibu Shinjuku Line|ja|西武新宿線}}.{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}}
* From {{ill|Ogikubo Station|ja|荻窪駅}} on the {{ill|JR Chūō Main Line|ja|中央本線}}, 20 minutes by bus. From {{ill|Mitaka Station|ja|三鷹駅}}, 10 minutes by bus. Alight at "Sekimachikita 2-chome," then 1 minute's walk.{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}}

