'''Tenso Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine''' (天祖若宮八幡宮) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in Sekimachikita 3-chome, [[:en:Nerima|Nerima Ward]], [[:en:Tokyo|Tokyo Metropolis]], Japan. The shrine is situated atop a hill in [[:en:Musashiseki Park|Musashiseki Park]], maintained by Nerima Ward.

== Overview ==

In [[:en:1974|1974]] ([[:en:Shōwa era|Shōwa]] 49), Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine and Tenso Shrine were merged and began to be collectively referred to as Tenso Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine.{{sfn|Nerima Ward Board of Education}}{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}} The enshrined deities include {{ill|Ōhirume-no-Muchi-no-Mikoto|ja|大日孁貴女尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōhirume-no-Muchi-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天照大神|1=Amaterasu|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q455602}}, {{ill|Sayori Hime no Mikoto|ja|狭依姫命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sayori Hime no Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, and {{ill|Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|ja|倉稲魂命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to ウカノミタマ|1=Ukanomitama|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q3080728}} at Tenso Shrine. Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine venerates {{ill|Hachiman Ōkami|ja|八幡大神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiman Ōkami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 八幡神|1=Hachiman|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q261637}}, identified with [[:en:Emperor Ōjin|Emperor Ōjin]], and [[:en:Emperor Nintoku|Emperor Nintoku]]. The main festival is held annually on September 28.{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}}

== History ==

[[File:天祖若宮八幡宮－２.jpg|thumb|Tenso Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine]]
[[File:天祖若宮八幡宮－３.jpg|thumb|Shrine grounds]]

Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine is said to have been established during the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]] as the guardian deity of the Musashi Seki Barrier.{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}} After the barrier was dismantled, it served as the [[:en:Ujigami|ujigami]] (guardian deity) of Sekimura, which encompasses present-day Sekimachikita, Sekimachi Minami, Sekimachi Higashi, and Tatemachi. The shrine's role was formalized during the [[:en:Keichō|Keichō era]] with the opening of Sekimura.

Tenso Shrine was originally referred to as "Banjin-sama" (番神さま), as described in the "Sekimura" section of the {{ill|Shinpen Musashi Fudokikō|ja|新編武蔵風土記稿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinpen Musashi Fudokikō|qq=|1=Shinpen Musashi Fudoki-kō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11503943}}: "The Banshin Shrine is the village's guardian deity and belongs to {{ill|Hondatsugi Temple|ja|本立寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hondatsugi Temple|qq=|1=Hondatsugi Temple|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11520735}}."<ref>{{cite book|和書|title=新編武蔵風土記稿|volume=Volume 13, Toshima District Part 5|chapter=Sekimura|id={{NDLJP|763977/46}}|publisher=Geographical Bureau, Ministry of Home Affairs|date=1884-6}}</ref> During the [[:en:Meiji Restoration|Meiji Restoration]], it was renamed Tenso Shrine due to the policy of [[:en:Shinbutsu bunri|Shinbutsu bunri]].

== Transportation ==

The shrine is surrounded by dense greenery and forms part of the verdant landscape of Musashino, along with [[:en:Musashiseki Park|Musashiseki Park]], which features a boating pond.

* 5 minutes' walk from [[:en:Musashi-Seki Station|Musashiseki Station]] on the [[:en:Seibu Shinjuku Line|Seibu Shinjuku Line]].{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}}
* From [[:en:Ogikubo Station|Ogikubo Station]] on the [[:en:Chūō Main Line|JR Chūō Main Line]], 20 minutes by bus. From [[:en:Mitaka Station|Mitaka Station]], 10 minutes by bus. Alight at "Sekimachikita 2-chome," then 1 minute's walk.{{sfn|Tokyo Shrine Agency}}

